WEBVTT

00:01.251 --> 00:03.341
Take care of him.

00:03.462 --> 00:05.842
What aren’t you telling me
about your man in Scotland?

00:05.923 --> 00:07.633
He’s Bree’s real father,

00:07.716 --> 00:09.336
and I told her

00:09.468 --> 00:10.838
when we were in Scotland.

00:10.969 --> 00:13.889
KNOX:
I admire a man who puts
duty and honor above all else.

00:14.014 --> 00:16.354
It’s only civility
that keeps us all
from killing one another.

00:16.433 --> 00:18.813
What have you done?

00:18.894 --> 00:21.274
You executed a man
without trial!

00:21.355 --> 00:23.445
Stick out your tongue.

00:23.524 --> 00:26.194
Kezzie.
His tonsils are as infected
as his brother’s.

00:26.276 --> 00:28.526
Then you must return with him
to the Ridge.

00:28.612 --> 00:29.902
You will escort Claire home.

00:30.030 --> 00:31.070
What about the militia?

00:31.198 --> 00:32.528
I made ye a captain

00:32.616 --> 00:34.406
without time to teach ye
what the word meant.

00:34.535 --> 00:36.875
[ sweeping orchestral music ]

00:36.995 --> 00:37.865
JAMIE:
Couldna tell ye
at the wedding.

00:37.955 --> 00:39.255
I wanted to be certain.

00:39.373 --> 00:41.423
Confirmed sightings
of Bonnet in Wilmington.

00:41.542 --> 00:42.382
[ man yells ]

00:44.545 --> 00:48.555
CHANTER:
♪ All glory and honor
is yours ♪

00:48.632 --> 00:53.512
♪ Forever and ever ♪

00:53.595 --> 00:58.555
♪ Amen ♪

00:58.642 --> 01:01.392
[ melancholy music ]

01:01.520 --> 01:05.020
♪

01:06.024 --> 01:10.154
CLAIRE:
How many times
have I put my hopes, my fears,

01:10.237 --> 01:12.197
my secret longings

01:12.281 --> 01:15.451
into the hands of a being
I can’t see,

01:15.576 --> 01:17.536
can’t hear,

01:17.619 --> 01:19.579
can’t even feel?

01:19.663 --> 01:22.923
♪

01:23.000 --> 01:25.500
And how many times
have my prayers been answered?

01:25.586 --> 01:28.756
♪

01:46.898 --> 01:49.778
[ gasping softly ]

01:49.860 --> 01:52.240
[ warm music ]

01:52.321 --> 01:53.281
[ footsteps tapping ]

01:53.405 --> 01:56.325
♪

01:56.450 --> 01:58.830
What is it?

01:58.952 --> 02:00.622
Come and look.

02:00.704 --> 02:03.794
♪

02:07.252 --> 02:09.342
It’s paintbrushes.

02:09.463 --> 02:11.803
♪

02:11.923 --> 02:14.633
Paintbrushes.
[ laughs ]

02:14.718 --> 02:16.638
♪

02:16.762 --> 02:19.062
Ye found it?

02:19.139 --> 02:20.139
[ laughs ]

02:20.265 --> 02:21.515
I think what we’re
supposed to say

02:21.642 --> 02:23.522
is "eureka."

02:23.644 --> 02:25.774
[ laughs ]
Uh, what does that mean?

02:25.854 --> 02:27.694
[ laughter ]

02:27.814 --> 02:31.114
It means, well,
"I’ve found it."

02:31.193 --> 02:32.903
[ laughs ]

02:32.986 --> 02:36.606
Well, uh, eureka, Claire.

02:36.698 --> 02:39.578
[ laughs ]

02:39.660 --> 02:41.620
Ye found yer penicillin.

02:41.703 --> 02:44.833
♪

02:45.666 --> 02:46.996
[ laughs ]

02:48.669 --> 02:50.839
CHOIR:
♪ Sing me a song ♪

02:50.921 --> 02:53.921
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

02:54.007 --> 02:56.217
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

02:56.343 --> 02:59.553
♪ Be I? ♪

02:59.680 --> 03:01.640
♪ Merry of soul ♪

03:01.723 --> 03:04.773
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

03:04.851 --> 03:06.691
♪ Over the sea ♪

03:06.770 --> 03:09.940
♪ To Skye ♪

03:10.023 --> 03:12.613
♪ Billow and breeze ♪

03:12.693 --> 03:15.113
♪ Islands and seas ♪

03:15.195 --> 03:18.065
♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪

03:18.198 --> 03:20.658
♪ Mountains of rain
and sun ♪

03:20.742 --> 03:23.042
♪ All that was good ♪

03:23.120 --> 03:25.620
♪ All that was fair ♪

03:25.706 --> 03:27.786
♪ All that was me ♪

03:27.874 --> 03:30.754
♪ Is gone ♪

03:30.877 --> 03:32.997
♪ Sing me a song ♪

03:33.088 --> 03:35.918
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

03:36.049 --> 03:38.179
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

03:38.260 --> 03:41.300
♪ Be I? ♪

03:41.388 --> 03:43.428
♪ Merry of soul ♪

03:43.557 --> 03:46.557
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

03:46.643 --> 03:50.733
♪ Over the sea ♪

03:50.814 --> 03:56.744
♪ To Skye ♪

03:56.820 --> 03:59.660
[ dramatic music ]

03:59.740 --> 04:02.160
♪

04:02.242 --> 04:06.582
WOMAN:
♪ Sing me a song ♪

04:06.663 --> 04:08.753
♪ Of a lass ♪

04:08.832 --> 04:11.962
♪ That is gone ♪

04:12.085 --> 04:16.795
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

04:16.923 --> 04:20.553
♪ Be I? ♪

04:20.635 --> 04:22.635
♪

04:22.763 --> 04:25.933
CLAIRE:
Time is a lot of the things
that people say God is.

04:26.057 --> 04:28.387
There’s the preexisting
and having no end.

04:28.477 --> 04:30.847
There’s the notion
of being all‐powerful,

04:30.937 --> 04:33.147
because nothing
can stand against time,

04:33.273 --> 04:36.193
not mountains, not armies.

04:36.276 --> 04:39.396
Give anything enough time,
and everything
is taken care of:

04:39.488 --> 04:42.778
all pain encompassed,
all hardship erased,

04:42.866 --> 04:44.776
all loss subsumed.

04:44.868 --> 04:47.658
Ashes to ashes,
dust to dust.

04:47.788 --> 04:50.118
Remember, Man,
thou art dust,

04:50.207 --> 04:52.827
and unto dust
thou shalt return.

04:52.959 --> 04:57.299
And if time is anything
akin to God,

04:57.380 --> 05:00.220
I suppose that memory
must be the devil.

05:04.137 --> 05:05.347
BRIANNA:
Sorry I’m late.

05:05.472 --> 05:06.512
That’s all right.

05:06.640 --> 05:09.020
Plenty of time
to get to the restaurant.

05:09.142 --> 05:10.982
Lunch at Jeveli’s.

05:11.102 --> 05:12.652
One of us must have done
something good.

05:12.729 --> 05:14.149
[ laughs ]

05:14.231 --> 05:16.151
Is everything okay?

05:16.233 --> 05:18.693
You sounded kind of weird
on the phone.

05:18.819 --> 05:19.939
Yeah.

05:25.158 --> 05:27.408
Actually, I...
[ sighs ]

05:27.494 --> 05:29.874
I just lost a patient.

05:29.996 --> 05:32.616
Oh, wow. I’m sorry.

05:33.458 --> 05:36.668
He had an allergic reaction
to penicillin.

05:36.795 --> 05:38.215
Don’t we have tests for that?

05:38.338 --> 05:39.958
[ sighs ]

05:40.048 --> 05:42.508
He tested negative.

05:42.592 --> 05:46.352
The probability
of a false positive
is less than 5%.

05:46.471 --> 05:48.471
It’s very rare.

05:48.557 --> 05:51.097
Unfortunately, he was part
of that percentile.

05:52.769 --> 05:54.519
Man.

05:54.604 --> 05:56.564
I guess you never really know
what’s coming, do you?

05:56.690 --> 05:57.980
[ melancholy music ]

05:58.066 --> 05:59.686
No, you don’t.

05:59.818 --> 06:02.698
♪

06:08.201 --> 06:11.411
ROGER:
Did you...enjoy yourself?

06:13.540 --> 06:15.290
Aye, Captain.

06:15.375 --> 06:18.035
[ laughs ]

06:23.842 --> 06:26.052
Well, I’m delighted

06:26.136 --> 06:28.636
to have pleased you,
Mrs. Mac.

06:30.265 --> 06:33.485
But if it’s a military man
who takes your fancy...

06:35.562 --> 06:38.562
[ with English accent ]
Methinks you sell yourself
short, my darling.

06:40.025 --> 06:41.735
Accent hasn’t improved much,
I see.

06:41.818 --> 06:44.698
[ laughs ] No.

06:44.779 --> 06:47.449
If yer father agreed with you,
I’d be out leading the charge,

06:47.574 --> 06:50.034
not sent home
from Brownsville.

06:56.499 --> 07:00.089
The Brownsville thing
doesn’t seem that bad to me.

07:00.170 --> 07:02.260
Mama said people
were actually

07:02.339 --> 07:04.759
singing and dancing
when they arrived.

07:04.883 --> 07:07.093
Hmm.

07:08.929 --> 07:11.849
You know how to get through
to people.

07:11.932 --> 07:14.102
It’s no wonder
they loved you at Oxford.

07:15.894 --> 07:20.734
Well, you know, I had time
to think on my long ride home.

07:20.815 --> 07:23.935
There are already universities
established here.

07:24.069 --> 07:27.699
Harvard, Yale...

07:27.781 --> 07:29.201
MacKenzie University.

07:29.282 --> 07:33.082
[ laughs ]
There’s no
MacKenzie University.

07:33.161 --> 07:36.211
Not yet, but then...

07:40.877 --> 07:43.797
That’s not a bad idea,
actually.

07:43.880 --> 07:45.550
I could teach math.

07:45.632 --> 07:47.932
Honestly, I was just
passing time,

07:48.009 --> 07:49.969
thinking about the old days.

07:50.095 --> 07:52.145
Things being what they are...

07:54.516 --> 07:57.556
Anyway, I gave my oath
to your father

07:57.644 --> 08:00.024
to be in his militia,

08:00.146 --> 08:03.146
and those words
mean something to him...

08:03.233 --> 08:04.573
and to me.

08:07.821 --> 08:08.861
Yeah.

08:08.989 --> 08:11.569
[ laughs ]

08:11.658 --> 08:14.488
[ thunder rumbling ]

08:15.912 --> 08:18.122
[ horse neighs ]

08:18.206 --> 08:21.036
[ uneasy music ]

08:21.167 --> 08:24.297
♪

08:44.024 --> 08:46.484
Not the cordial welcome
I’d expect.

08:46.568 --> 08:48.188
Friendly buggers,
aren’t they?

08:48.319 --> 08:49.699
Yeah, they think
we’re Regulators.

08:49.779 --> 08:51.739
MAN:
We don’t want trouble again.

08:52.407 --> 08:54.487
If you’ve come to violate
the king’s peace,

08:54.576 --> 08:58.326
there’s a brigade
of redcoats at hand,

08:58.413 --> 09:00.503
ready to give ye
a sound thrashing.

09:00.582 --> 09:03.132
We’ve no quarrel
with you, neighbor.

09:03.209 --> 09:05.339
On the contrary.

09:05.420 --> 09:08.340
Colonel James Fraser
of Rowan County Militia,

09:08.423 --> 09:11.553
assembled according
to Governor Tyron’s orders.

09:11.634 --> 09:13.594
Then we welcome you
and bless you
for your kindness.

09:14.387 --> 09:15.887
Not kindness alone.

09:20.560 --> 09:23.400
Governor Tryon has promised

09:23.480 --> 09:26.980
40 shillings
for every man who enlists.

09:27.067 --> 09:29.237
Is there anyone here

09:29.360 --> 09:31.200
willing to take up arms
and join us?

09:31.279 --> 09:33.819
[ laughter, men muttering ]

09:35.450 --> 09:37.580
Is that what our lives
are deemed to be worth?

09:38.703 --> 09:42.253
There’s no price that can be
put upon a man’s bravery.

09:42.332 --> 09:43.792
No doubt
the strength of spirit

09:43.917 --> 09:45.497
speaks louder
than the strength of body.

09:46.878 --> 09:49.798
We do aim to keep you
in good spirits, however,

09:49.923 --> 09:52.633
with our shops and the like.

09:52.759 --> 09:56.099
The redcoats are benefiting
from our hospitality

09:56.221 --> 09:58.761
as we speak.

09:58.890 --> 09:59.890
Where are they?

09:59.974 --> 10:01.604
William Reed’s Ordinary.

10:04.270 --> 10:05.650
[ indistinct chatter ]

10:05.772 --> 10:07.942
[ men cheering ]

10:08.066 --> 10:10.606
JAMIE:
Uh, buy a cask of rum,
have the garrison make camp,

10:10.735 --> 10:13.605
and let them drink
till the barrel runs dry.

10:13.696 --> 10:17.276
Say no more, Colonel.
Your command is our wish.

10:17.367 --> 10:19.487
Ah.
Did I not tell you
the colonel

10:19.619 --> 10:21.449
would arrive as promised?

10:21.579 --> 10:24.289
And with daylight to spare.

10:24.415 --> 10:27.995
And wi’, uh, a few more men
to stand wi’ us, Lieutenant.

10:28.128 --> 10:30.088
50 or so.

10:30.171 --> 10:32.511
Oh.
Fetch them both some ale.

10:40.348 --> 10:42.138
A little barbaric, I know,

10:42.267 --> 10:45.437
but in the absence
of more tangible pursuits...

10:47.021 --> 10:49.441
He leaves no trace.

10:49.524 --> 10:50.984
A shadow in the dark,
that one.

10:51.109 --> 10:52.319
Aye.

10:52.443 --> 10:54.493
I’m glad to see you,

10:54.571 --> 10:56.991
but there is
some unfortunate news
I must share...

10:58.825 --> 11:00.995
From Governor Tryon.

11:01.077 --> 11:02.407
The governor intends

11:02.495 --> 11:04.785
to pardon the leaders
of the Regulator movement.

11:07.125 --> 11:09.845
Full pardons...for everyone?

11:09.919 --> 11:11.339
Exactly.

11:11.421 --> 11:13.011
After everything
we’ve done,

11:13.131 --> 11:14.341
the progress we’ve made...

11:14.465 --> 11:16.875
He makes no mention
of why he’d order
such a thing?

11:17.010 --> 11:18.430
No.

11:18.511 --> 11:20.351
Appeasement, perhaps.

11:21.890 --> 11:23.430
But I worry.

11:25.185 --> 11:28.655
Will it not make us
look foolish
or cowardly, even,

11:28.730 --> 11:30.060
in the eyes
of our subordinates?

11:30.190 --> 11:31.940
Aye, maybe.

11:34.569 --> 11:37.109
As you know,
I did something...

11:37.197 --> 11:40.317
excessive in the jail.

11:40.408 --> 11:42.238
I cannot face knowing

11:42.368 --> 11:43.908
that it might have been
for nothing.

11:44.037 --> 11:45.827
Maybe it’s for the best.

11:47.749 --> 11:50.039
Every man deserves
a second chance.

11:50.126 --> 11:52.036
But if you had taken the life
of an incarcerated man‐‐

11:52.170 --> 11:55.550
You must ask
the Lord’s forgiveness
and receive it.

11:57.050 --> 11:58.260
Trust me.

11:59.010 --> 12:01.390
There will be
other battles to fight.

12:13.358 --> 12:15.938
Yes, uh, I’m glad to be able
to call you a friend

12:16.069 --> 12:18.649
and to confide in you.

12:18.738 --> 12:20.738
It’s a shame.

12:20.865 --> 12:24.615
I am still holding on
to one small hope.

12:24.744 --> 12:29.374
I’m expecting a letter
which may give an indication
as to Fitzgibbons’ whereabouts.

12:30.541 --> 12:31.581
What d’ye mean?

12:31.709 --> 12:32.789
I petitioned the magistrate

12:32.919 --> 12:35.549
for the prisoner rolls
at Ardsmuir.

12:35.630 --> 12:38.720
I discovered Fitzgibbons
was once incarcerated there.

12:38.800 --> 12:42.640
You believe there may be
fellow prisoners

12:42.762 --> 12:46.142
residing here in the colonies
that might be hiding him?

12:46.266 --> 12:47.176
[ uneasy music ]

12:47.267 --> 12:49.767
Leave no stone unturned.

12:49.894 --> 12:51.354
Aye.

12:51.437 --> 12:54.187
As ye say...

12:54.274 --> 12:56.324
’tis all for naught.

12:56.442 --> 12:59.362
♪

12:59.445 --> 13:02.105
Here, have a go.

13:03.324 --> 13:04.954
Ah.

13:05.034 --> 13:07.664
Uh, the pardon doesna extend
to the man’s image, then?

13:07.787 --> 13:08.827
Mm.

13:08.955 --> 13:10.295
This may be as close
as we come.

13:10.373 --> 13:12.043
Mm.

13:12.125 --> 13:13.135
Maybe.

13:13.209 --> 13:15.419
♪

13:15.503 --> 13:18.213
Between the eyes, Colonel.

13:18.298 --> 13:21.758
CLAIRE:
As a child, I used
to stare at spiderwebs,

13:21.843 --> 13:25.223
watching and waiting
for an insect to become caught.

13:25.305 --> 13:29.485
While part of me was horrified
by watching the death throes,

13:29.559 --> 13:32.599
I was mesmerized by the way
the tiniest vibrations
in the web

13:32.687 --> 13:35.817
would signal the spider
that her prey was near.

13:35.898 --> 13:39.898
I wonder, is time
God’s eternal web,

13:39.986 --> 13:42.946
silk strands stretching
through time,

13:43.031 --> 13:45.321
the mildest touch
setting off vibrations

13:45.450 --> 13:47.160
that echo through the eons?

13:47.285 --> 13:49.205
♪

13:49.329 --> 13:51.039
Well, it’s about time.

13:51.164 --> 13:52.624
Is that cigarette smoke?

13:52.707 --> 13:54.457
[ sniffs ]
I don’t smell anything.

13:55.293 --> 13:57.463
You need to give those up.

13:57.545 --> 13:59.755
You certainly are chipper
this morning.

13:59.839 --> 14:02.719
Giving the nurses
a run for their money, I hear.

14:02.842 --> 14:05.302
I can’t help it
if Nurse Jeffries
has taken a shine to me.

14:05.386 --> 14:06.756
[ chuckles softly ]

14:06.846 --> 14:09.176
Go on, give it
to me straight,

14:09.265 --> 14:11.515
and no doctor mumbo‐jumbo, eh?

14:13.227 --> 14:14.597
All right.

14:18.691 --> 14:21.991
You have gallstones.

14:22.070 --> 14:23.070
Gallstones?

14:23.196 --> 14:24.696
‐ Mm.
‐ Is that it?

14:24.822 --> 14:27.702
I thought you were going to use
the C word, cancer.

14:28.701 --> 14:32.001
Well, there is another C word
I have to use, unfortunately.

14:32.080 --> 14:36.540
Cholangitis, an infection
in your bile ducts.

14:36.626 --> 14:39.796
I can treat that
with an antibiotic,

14:39.879 --> 14:41.459
but the gallstones
are rather large,

14:41.547 --> 14:44.087
too large to pass naturally.

14:44.217 --> 14:46.547
You’ll need a cholecystectomy,

14:46.636 --> 14:49.216
surgery to remove
the gallbladder.

14:49.305 --> 14:50.555
Dr. Randall‐‐

14:50.681 --> 14:53.101
Randall, that’s a good
English name, that...

14:53.226 --> 14:55.136
It’s my married name.

14:55.228 --> 14:58.438
What you’re proposin’
seems quite personal to me.

14:58.564 --> 15:00.734
Be nice if we were on
a first‐name basis.

15:02.693 --> 15:04.863
Mr. Menzies, I do need you
to keep focused.

15:04.946 --> 15:06.026
See?

15:06.114 --> 15:08.204
See, I can tell a Scot
when I see one.

15:08.282 --> 15:10.412
You have some Scottish blood
running through you somehow.

15:10.535 --> 15:12.455
I consider myself American
these days.

15:12.578 --> 15:14.408
Ah, no shame in it.

15:14.497 --> 15:16.367
I married a Yank as well.

15:16.457 --> 15:18.537
He wasn’t a Yank, actually.

15:18.626 --> 15:21.246
She passed away.

15:21.337 --> 15:23.667
My Olivia.

15:23.756 --> 15:27.256
Would you believe,
lived here for more
than 20 years,

15:27.343 --> 15:31.063
and still no one understands
a damn word I’m saying?

15:31.139 --> 15:34.019
[ gentle music ]

15:34.100 --> 15:36.520
You have a knack
for getting me off topic.

15:36.602 --> 15:37.442
[ laughs ]

15:37.520 --> 15:39.520
♪

15:39.605 --> 15:43.145
May I go back
to discussing your surgery
without interruption, please?

15:43.276 --> 15:45.606
If ye must.
[ grunts ]

15:45.736 --> 15:48.906
The incision is generally
between five and seven inches

15:48.990 --> 15:51.120
in the upper right section
of your belly,

15:51.242 --> 15:52.532
just below the ribs.

15:52.618 --> 15:54.948
You’re gonna gut me
like a fish, then?

15:55.079 --> 15:56.619
Yes,

15:56.747 --> 15:58.077
but first,
I’d like to start you

15:58.166 --> 16:01.286
on a course of antibiotics
to treat the infection.

16:01.377 --> 16:04.207
I’ll have Nurse Jeffries
run some preliminary tests

16:04.297 --> 16:06.007
for allergies and such.

16:06.132 --> 16:08.472
I don’t suppose
there are any other options.

16:08.551 --> 16:10.011
I’m afraid not.

16:10.136 --> 16:11.386
♪

16:11.471 --> 16:13.351
Well, let’s go on
with it, then.

16:13.473 --> 16:16.643
[ sighs ]
It’s but one more scar,

16:16.726 --> 16:18.306
nothing worth broodin’ over.

16:18.436 --> 16:21.606
♪

16:26.611 --> 16:29.151
No swollen tongue or lips.

16:32.158 --> 16:34.448
No rash...

16:34.535 --> 16:36.245
or hives.

16:36.329 --> 16:37.659
Congratulations, Kezzie.

16:37.788 --> 16:39.998
It appears you’re not allergic
to penicillin.

16:47.673 --> 16:48.923
So the mold worked?

16:50.176 --> 16:52.086
As far as I can tell.

16:56.891 --> 16:58.141
What?
Ye dinna sound certain, Claire.

17:01.020 --> 17:03.810
Well, the test
isn’t always reliable.

17:03.898 --> 17:06.858
Aye, but ye think
all will be well?

17:08.694 --> 17:11.864
Everything you do as a doctor
involves risk.

17:11.948 --> 17:14.868
Even after you’ve done
everything you can,

17:14.951 --> 17:17.661
there could still be
unforeseen complications,

17:17.745 --> 17:19.825
sometimes even fatal.

17:21.207 --> 17:23.037
The more you can do
to alleviate the risk,

17:23.125 --> 17:24.955
the greater the chance
to save the patient.

17:25.044 --> 17:26.054
Mm.

17:26.170 --> 17:29.550
Now, this dose...

17:29.674 --> 17:32.724
should start the fight
against the infection.

17:39.934 --> 17:42.774
Bring over the other
sterilized instruments, please.

17:43.938 --> 17:46.938
All right, Kezzie.
Drop your britches.

17:59.620 --> 18:00.750
[ winces ]

18:02.164 --> 18:05.044
[ uneasy music ]

18:05.126 --> 18:06.956
♪

18:07.086 --> 18:09.586
Now...

18:09.714 --> 18:12.224
Lizzie,
put the sheet on him.

18:14.260 --> 18:15.890
♪

18:15.970 --> 18:18.180
Mr. Bug,
hold his shoulders tight.

18:18.264 --> 18:19.564
Aye.

18:19.640 --> 18:20.600
Laudanum.

18:20.683 --> 18:23.813
♪

18:25.271 --> 18:28.611
This will start
to take effect quickly.

18:28.733 --> 18:30.823
Lizzie, keep the lantern
close by.

18:30.943 --> 18:33.283
Uh, yes, Mistress.

18:33.362 --> 18:34.492
♪

18:34.614 --> 18:35.574
CLAIRE:
Open wide.

18:35.656 --> 18:37.316
♪

18:37.450 --> 18:39.030
Hmm.

18:39.118 --> 18:40.788
Well, I’m going
to work quickly,

18:40.870 --> 18:42.330
but you need to keep
very still.

18:42.455 --> 18:44.545
♪

18:44.624 --> 18:45.964
Head up.

18:46.042 --> 18:47.422
Cork.

18:47.501 --> 18:50.381
♪

18:52.089 --> 18:54.259
Right, just as we practiced.

18:54.342 --> 18:56.342
Scalpel.

18:56.469 --> 18:59.469
♪

18:59.764 --> 19:01.184
[ squelching ]

19:01.307 --> 19:04.597
[ Kezzie groans ]

19:04.685 --> 19:05.885
CLAIRE:
Ooh.

19:05.978 --> 19:07.728
Keep the tongue depressed.

19:07.813 --> 19:09.113
[ Kezzie groans ]

19:09.190 --> 19:11.070
♪

19:11.150 --> 19:13.360
There.

19:13.486 --> 19:14.776
♪

19:14.862 --> 19:18.162
Head up.
Hold that in there.

19:18.240 --> 19:20.330
Right, I’m going to have
to cauterize the tissue.

19:20.409 --> 19:21.619
♪

19:21.702 --> 19:22.912
Steady.

19:22.995 --> 19:24.325
This can be the tricky part.

19:24.455 --> 19:25.665
♪

19:25.790 --> 19:29.460
‐ [ tissue hisses ]
‐ [ groaning ]

19:29.543 --> 19:30.843
♪

19:30.920 --> 19:32.340
CLAIRE:
There.

19:32.421 --> 19:33.841
Done.

19:33.964 --> 19:35.634
[ relieved music ]

19:35.716 --> 19:37.546
[ groans ]

19:37.677 --> 19:38.837
[ laughs ]

19:38.928 --> 19:40.718
Lizzie, you can open
your eyes now.

19:40.846 --> 19:42.256
Holy mother of God.

19:43.557 --> 19:44.677
CLAIRE:
Are you all right?

19:44.767 --> 19:47.597
[ serene music ]

19:47.687 --> 19:49.097
♪

19:49.188 --> 19:52.108
You’re very, very brave,
Kezzie.

19:52.191 --> 19:54.031
Now, you need to get
your rest.

19:54.110 --> 19:57.280
Lizzie, can you clean him up
and put him to bed?

19:57.363 --> 19:59.623
‐ Mm‐‐
‐ CLAIRE: No, don’t try
to talk.

19:59.699 --> 20:00.619
You’ll hurt yourself.

20:00.700 --> 20:03.870
♪

20:05.371 --> 20:07.371
He insists on stayin’
while ye do the same for me.

20:07.498 --> 20:09.708
♪

20:09.834 --> 20:11.924
Then I suppose
we should get started.

20:12.044 --> 20:16.594
[ baby squalling ]

20:16.716 --> 20:17.966
Jem, look, look.

20:18.050 --> 20:19.800
Hey, Jem, look.

20:19.885 --> 20:22.465
Shiny.

20:22.555 --> 20:26.985
CLAIRE:
Is God the spider,

20:27.059 --> 20:31.229
embracing us
through our death
and resurrection,

20:31.355 --> 20:34.895
or is he simply
the spinner of the web,

20:34.984 --> 20:37.744
watching as the silk
shimmers and vibrates

20:37.820 --> 20:39.530
through the cosmos...

20:39.613 --> 20:41.453
♪

20:41.574 --> 20:44.244
[ disquieting music ]

20:44.326 --> 20:46.996
Awakening the real spiders,

20:47.079 --> 20:50.079
the ones lurking
deep within the recesses

20:50.166 --> 20:51.706
of our own natures?

20:51.792 --> 20:54.922
♪

20:57.757 --> 21:00.587
I was going to wager
this rare beauty.

21:00.718 --> 21:03.178
♪

21:03.262 --> 21:04.892
Double or quits
the last card.

21:07.600 --> 21:12.400
Women will do anything
for trinkets, coins, jewels.

21:12.480 --> 21:13.610
Anything at all.

21:16.317 --> 21:18.237
They’re yours
for a pretty penny...

21:18.319 --> 21:21.279
or a diamond...

21:21.363 --> 21:22.573
or a ring.

21:29.288 --> 21:31.538
My lass is more concerned
wi’ words and deeds.

21:33.501 --> 21:35.251
Is that so?

21:45.179 --> 21:48.099
Since you’ve no need
of the gemstone,

21:48.182 --> 21:49.602
perhaps you’ll be
more satisfied

21:49.683 --> 21:51.943
with my pearls of wisdom.

21:54.230 --> 21:56.980
Women are but a tax
we men pay on pleasure.

22:09.495 --> 22:12.125
Did you not play
the ace of hearts
in the last hand?

22:15.960 --> 22:18.170
You’re mistaken.

22:24.260 --> 22:26.510
It must have been
the ace of diamonds.

22:27.763 --> 22:29.263
[ slams table ]

22:29.849 --> 22:32.349
You’re a wise man,
Mr. MacKenzie.

22:32.434 --> 22:35.354
[ uneasy music ]

22:35.479 --> 22:38.359
♪

22:53.289 --> 22:55.209
I wanted to make
mushroom soup.

22:55.291 --> 22:58.251
Didn’t think
I’d be gone so long.

22:58.377 --> 23:00.247
I was looking
for chanterelles
but couldn’t find any.

23:00.379 --> 23:03.299
[ baby coughs and fusses ]

23:04.758 --> 23:06.298
Was he a handful?

23:09.221 --> 23:10.261
What is this?

23:19.148 --> 23:20.608
It’s Bonnet’s, isn’t it?

23:34.246 --> 23:38.076
I wanted to tell you
about this, but...

23:39.752 --> 23:42.212
[ sighs ]

23:42.296 --> 23:44.966
I was afraid
you wouldn’t understand.

23:45.090 --> 23:46.590
Try me.

23:50.346 --> 23:54.976
You know that I went
to Wilmington to see him.

23:55.100 --> 23:58.150
What you said was,
you went to see him hanged.

23:58.270 --> 24:01.570
I did, but...

24:04.276 --> 24:08.276
When I got there, I...

24:08.405 --> 24:12.775
I felt like I needed
to see him in person.

24:12.868 --> 24:14.868
So you spoke to him,

24:14.954 --> 24:17.464
there, in jail?

24:17.581 --> 24:20.131
Yeah.

24:20.209 --> 24:22.419
That’s when he gave me
the diamond.

24:22.503 --> 24:24.553
And you kept it?

24:24.630 --> 24:27.760
A gift...from Bonnet?

24:27.841 --> 24:30.471
I kept it for Jemmy,

24:30.594 --> 24:33.974
so that one day,
he could go back
through the stones.

24:34.098 --> 24:36.098
R‐Roger, that’s
his ticket home.

24:36.183 --> 24:37.813
It’s our ticket home.

24:37.893 --> 24:40.773
[ tense music ]

24:40.854 --> 24:43.734
♪

24:48.070 --> 24:49.780
Why, though?

24:49.863 --> 24:52.243
♪

24:52.324 --> 24:53.494
Why?

24:53.617 --> 24:55.787
♪

24:55.869 --> 24:57.869
The Stephen Bonnet I knew
wouldn’t give up this diamond

24:57.997 --> 24:59.827
to save his own mother’s life.

24:59.957 --> 25:02.707
[ melancholy music ]

25:02.835 --> 25:04.135
♪

25:04.211 --> 25:05.751
[ breathes raggedly ]

25:05.838 --> 25:07.708
Bree...

25:07.840 --> 25:10.720
♪

25:14.096 --> 25:17.846
[ sighs ]
Because...

25:17.975 --> 25:20.985
♪

25:21.061 --> 25:23.271
Because I told him
Jemmy was his.

25:24.231 --> 25:26.571
He‐he was gonna die,

25:26.692 --> 25:30.202
and I thought
that it would be of comfort

25:30.279 --> 25:32.199
for him
to know there’d be

25:32.322 --> 25:35.282
something of his
left in this world.

25:35.367 --> 25:37.787
Roger, I am so sorry.

25:37.870 --> 25:40.500
I am so sorry.

25:40.581 --> 25:43.121
I‐I didn’t know
if you were coming back,

25:43.208 --> 25:45.998
and I was scared,
and I was grieving for you.

25:46.086 --> 25:47.876
♪

25:48.005 --> 25:50.175
They were just words,

25:50.257 --> 25:53.217
words you were never, ever
meant to hear.

25:53.302 --> 25:55.602
Words have consequences.

25:55.721 --> 25:58.601
♪

26:03.479 --> 26:07.729
All these months
since I’ve been back,

26:07.858 --> 26:10.148
at the wedding,

26:10.235 --> 26:12.605
the blood oath,

26:12.738 --> 26:15.318
you were sure
the child was Bonnet’s.

26:15.407 --> 26:18.697
Roger, how could I ever know
for sure that Jemmy is his?

26:18.786 --> 26:20.576
You told him so.

26:20.662 --> 26:22.582
You’ve never said
as much to me.

26:22.706 --> 26:25.456
♪

26:25.584 --> 26:29.384
I didn’t think I needed to.

26:29.463 --> 26:31.423
Brianna, what do you
truly believe?

26:32.716 --> 26:35.426
In your heart,
what do you truly believe?

26:35.511 --> 26:38.431
♪

27:01.453 --> 27:03.623
[ door latch clacks ]

27:05.958 --> 27:07.958
[ door slams ]

27:08.085 --> 27:09.845
♪

27:09.962 --> 27:13.052
[ sobs ]

27:13.132 --> 27:15.972
[ church bell ringing ]

27:16.051 --> 27:18.971
♪

27:38.991 --> 27:41.701
I don’t believe I’ve seen you
at the adoration before.

27:41.827 --> 27:43.367
Were you a friend
of Mr. Menzies’?

27:43.495 --> 27:45.615
Claire Randall.

27:45.706 --> 27:49.376
I’m his surgeon,
or I would have been.

27:50.460 --> 27:52.210
Graham was
a rare individual.

27:52.337 --> 27:54.007
Always brought a smile
to my face.

27:54.131 --> 27:56.171
Yes, he was good at that.

27:56.300 --> 27:57.720
Do you mind?

27:57.843 --> 27:58.723
Oh, please.

28:04.016 --> 28:05.306
Did you know him well?

28:07.269 --> 28:10.649
No...not in the typical sense.

28:13.525 --> 28:16.605
To be honest,
I’m‐I’m not quite sure
why I’m here.

28:19.531 --> 28:22.451
Sometimes even strangers
can find a way into our hearts.

28:25.120 --> 28:28.620
No, what little
I did know of Graham

28:28.707 --> 28:32.207
was how sacred
he held this time.

28:32.294 --> 28:34.594
[ gentle music ]

28:34.713 --> 28:37.133
The promise he made
to his wife to be here.

28:37.216 --> 28:38.836
♪

28:38.926 --> 28:43.006
Outside the love that God has
for his children...

28:43.096 --> 28:46.096
that sort of love and devotion
between man and wife,

28:46.225 --> 28:47.895
there’s nothing like it.

28:47.976 --> 28:50.896
♪

28:53.190 --> 28:54.690
Yes.

28:54.775 --> 28:57.155
♪

28:57.236 --> 29:00.776
It reminded me of someone.

29:00.906 --> 29:03.776
♪

29:04.409 --> 29:06.239
Someone I lost.

29:06.328 --> 29:09.328
♪

29:09.414 --> 29:11.084
No one’s lost
who’s not forgotten.

29:11.208 --> 29:14.378
♪

29:17.839 --> 29:20.759
Perhaps I just needed
to be reminded of that.

29:20.884 --> 29:23.764
♪

29:32.729 --> 29:35.689
[ insects and birds chirping ]

29:38.360 --> 29:41.400
[ leaves rustling ]

29:43.282 --> 29:46.122
[ suspenseful music ]

29:46.201 --> 29:49.121
♪

29:55.419 --> 29:56.539
Christ.

29:56.628 --> 29:58.798
‐ [ gasps ]
‐ Claire!

29:58.880 --> 30:00.380
Roger.

30:00.465 --> 30:03.465
I thought...

30:03.593 --> 30:05.303
I probably would’ve
missed you, but still.

30:05.429 --> 30:07.429
[ laughs ]

30:07.514 --> 30:09.184
You’re out early.

30:09.308 --> 30:13.268
Ah, I couldn’t sleep,
so I thought
I’d be productive,

30:13.353 --> 30:16.313
start looking
for some goldenseal

30:16.398 --> 30:19.068
for the twins’ recovery.

30:19.151 --> 30:20.441
I could say the same
about you.

30:20.527 --> 30:23.817
Ah, hunting...

30:23.905 --> 30:25.155
mostly.

30:26.950 --> 30:28.160
All night?

30:31.413 --> 30:32.833
It’s none of my business,
of course, but‐‐

30:32.956 --> 30:36.076
But you’re not buying
the...hunting ruse.

30:37.336 --> 30:41.006
Oh, call it
a mother’s intuition.

30:41.131 --> 30:43.881
Oh, I wish I had a bit
of a husband’s intuition.

30:44.926 --> 30:47.506
You haven’t been married
very long.

30:47.637 --> 30:50.217
Intuition comes
with listening and time.

30:50.349 --> 30:52.559
I have time in spades.

30:54.936 --> 30:58.766
Ah, take it from someone
with a lot of experience,

30:58.857 --> 31:02.397
but marriages
aren’t always easy.

31:02.527 --> 31:03.897
Well, you and Jamie...

31:04.029 --> 31:07.239
Oh, forgetting.

31:07.366 --> 31:10.156
Jamie wasn’t my first husband.

31:10.243 --> 31:12.253
Yeah, Frank and I...

31:12.371 --> 31:14.161
no, we had
a very complicated marriage.

31:14.247 --> 31:15.537
I’m sorry, Claire.

31:15.624 --> 31:17.384
I‐I didn’t mean to dredge up
old memories.

31:17.459 --> 31:19.249
No,

31:19.378 --> 31:21.498
I don’t mind talking about it.

31:22.714 --> 31:24.884
No, in fact, I’ve...

31:24.966 --> 31:27.506
been thinking about that time
a lot lately.

31:29.554 --> 31:32.144
Yeah, Frank and I, we...

31:32.224 --> 31:36.314
we still managed
to make it work
for Bree’s sake.

31:37.104 --> 31:39.114
But to make it work,
you had to lie to Brianna
for most of her life

31:39.231 --> 31:40.611
about her real father.

31:43.735 --> 31:45.525
Do you ever regret that?

31:47.906 --> 31:49.406
No.

31:50.492 --> 31:54.752
No, what was important
was that Bree
felt safe and loved

31:54.830 --> 31:56.870
by both her parents.

31:59.418 --> 32:01.878
[ pensive music ]

32:01.962 --> 32:04.882
♪

32:08.677 --> 32:11.757
But telling her the truth
about Jamie, that...

32:11.888 --> 32:14.138
brought the two of you closer.

32:14.266 --> 32:15.726
It did.

32:15.809 --> 32:17.599
So surely, the moral
of the story is,

32:17.727 --> 32:20.097
honesty is always
the best policy.

32:20.188 --> 32:22.108
♪

32:22.232 --> 32:25.032
Not always.

32:25.110 --> 32:28.910
Sometimes the truth
really does hurt.

32:28.989 --> 32:30.819
♪

32:30.949 --> 32:35.159
Brianna was devastated...

32:35.287 --> 32:36.787
and angry

32:36.913 --> 32:40.123
when I told her that Frank
wasn’t her real father.

32:40.250 --> 32:41.290
You witnessed that.

32:41.418 --> 32:44.128
♪

32:44.212 --> 32:47.512
There was no way
she could’ve understood
the truth as a child.

32:47.632 --> 32:50.302
♪

32:50.385 --> 32:52.135
It was difficult
for me as well.

32:52.220 --> 32:54.810
♪

32:54.890 --> 32:59.060
Trying to find
the right time to tell her...

32:59.144 --> 33:02.064
♪

33:02.731 --> 33:04.481
And, Roger,

33:04.608 --> 33:06.898
don’t be careless

33:06.985 --> 33:08.895
with the time
you have together.

33:08.987 --> 33:11.907
♪

33:15.494 --> 33:18.084
I appreciate
your honesty, Claire.

33:18.163 --> 33:21.083
♪

33:38.975 --> 33:41.845
I waded across the creek
and found some chanterelles.

33:41.937 --> 33:44.897
♪

33:49.194 --> 33:50.454
I want to explain.

33:50.529 --> 33:53.699
Doesn’t...doesn’t matter.

33:56.826 --> 33:58.786
I’m sorry, Brianna.

34:00.497 --> 34:02.997
I’m sorry for everything.

34:11.675 --> 34:13.135
There’s something else.

34:28.692 --> 34:30.492
Stephen Bonnet
is still alive.

34:30.569 --> 34:33.109
[ uneasy music ]

34:33.238 --> 34:34.488
What?

34:34.573 --> 34:37.493
And he haunts me, Roger.

34:37.576 --> 34:39.906
I see him everywhere.

34:39.995 --> 34:41.125
♪

34:41.246 --> 34:44.706
What’s worse is...

34:44.791 --> 34:48.421
Mrs. Bug told me
an Irishman approached her

34:48.503 --> 34:49.883
and spoke to Jemmy

34:49.963 --> 34:51.593
when we went
to Woolam’s Creek.

34:51.673 --> 34:54.763
♪

35:00.599 --> 35:03.429
That could’ve been anyone.

35:03.518 --> 35:07.188
And...Mrs. Bug’s
an old busybody.

35:07.272 --> 35:11.072
That might not
have been Bonnet, but...

35:11.151 --> 35:14.321
Lord John confirmed it
at our wedding

35:14.446 --> 35:17.316
that others have seen him
in Wilmington.

35:17.449 --> 35:20.329
♪

35:27.250 --> 35:28.750
Listen.

35:29.586 --> 35:30.836
Listen.

35:31.796 --> 35:34.916
♪

35:39.638 --> 35:41.558
I’m not gonna ask you
to explain why
you didn’t tell me.

35:41.640 --> 35:45.480
It doesn’t matter.
He...doesn’t matter.

35:45.560 --> 35:47.650
♪

35:47.771 --> 35:49.731
Because as soon as we know
if Jemmy can travel,

35:49.814 --> 35:52.944
we’ll use Bonnet’s gem
to leave.

35:53.026 --> 35:55.146
As you said,
it’s our ticket home.

35:55.278 --> 35:58.158
♪

36:10.835 --> 36:13.455
[ indistinct chatter ]

36:14.297 --> 36:17.047
A pardon for everyone
but Murtagh Fitzgibbons?

36:17.926 --> 36:19.336
Cunning maneuver,
isn’t it?

36:21.262 --> 36:24.722
Governor Tryon wants
to make an example of him.

36:24.849 --> 36:27.689
Well, treasonous behavior
of this sort

36:27.769 --> 36:30.269
is unforgivable,

36:30.355 --> 36:33.525
which is why His Excellency
has ordered me to continue
the hunt for Fitzgibbons.

36:34.693 --> 36:37.033
I’m relieved to hear it,

36:37.112 --> 36:40.702
but, uh, I fear
it’ll only encourage

36:40.782 --> 36:42.742
lawlessness
among the Regulators.

36:42.867 --> 36:46.367
Well, we are but
humble servants to the law.

36:47.622 --> 36:49.042
Aye.

36:49.124 --> 36:51.964
Those who follow
the path of the righteous

36:52.043 --> 36:53.503
shall have their reward.

36:55.380 --> 36:57.550
What will become
of the militia?

36:58.341 --> 37:01.301
Uh, you are to stand down
and hand over your muster roll.

37:01.386 --> 37:04.886
Then you and your men
can disband and go home.

37:05.014 --> 37:07.274
On your way,
you’ll deliver these pardons

37:07.392 --> 37:09.852
to those living in the counties
west of Hillsborough.

37:11.312 --> 37:14.072
Oh, I’ve no standing.
I’m no sheriff.

37:14.149 --> 37:16.569
No, but you are Scottish,

37:16.651 --> 37:18.861
as are many of the Regulators.

37:19.904 --> 37:24.034
From one Scot to another,
the governor would like you
to impress upon them

37:24.117 --> 37:26.577
his desire to be merciful

37:26.661 --> 37:29.251
and...just.

37:29.372 --> 37:30.922
Hmm.

37:31.040 --> 37:32.960
Well, my only regret
is not being able

37:33.084 --> 37:35.424
to assist you in your hunt
for Fitzgibbons.

37:36.713 --> 37:38.593
Allow me to worry about him.

37:39.841 --> 37:41.301
Return to your family.

37:41.426 --> 37:44.256
[ somber music ]

37:44.387 --> 37:45.967
♪

37:46.097 --> 37:47.597
GRAHAM:
You have to promise me
one thing.

37:48.516 --> 37:51.936
I’ll be back on my feet
by Friday at 4:00.

37:52.020 --> 37:54.690
It’s my
perpetual adoration shift
at St. Finbar’s.

37:55.273 --> 37:57.783
I have heard tell of that.

37:57.859 --> 37:59.489
Then you’ll know that someone
must be there at all times

37:59.611 --> 38:02.151
so the blessed sacrament
is never left alone.

38:02.280 --> 38:05.870
I haven’t missed a day
since Olivia died.

38:05.950 --> 38:08.950
It’s my way
of keeping her close.
[ laughs ]

38:09.037 --> 38:12.417
I like to think it’s her way
of keeping me close too.

38:12.499 --> 38:16.209
You know, sometimes
I feel her presence there.

38:16.294 --> 38:20.344
You remind me of someone
I met in Scotland years ago.

38:20.465 --> 38:21.975
We lost touch.

38:22.091 --> 38:24.301
He must have been a fool.

38:24.385 --> 38:26.045
[ sighs ]

38:26.137 --> 38:27.757
Well, if he was,
then I was equally so.

38:27.847 --> 38:29.967
Hmm.

38:30.058 --> 38:32.388
Scotland, eh?

38:32.477 --> 38:34.397
I never stop missing it.

38:34.479 --> 38:37.399
Always planned to get back
to the Western Isles.

38:37.482 --> 38:39.232
Well, maybe
once you’re on the mend.

38:39.317 --> 38:42.187
That time has passed,
I’m afraid.

38:42.320 --> 38:45.820
Uh, my wife, Olivia,
is buried here,
God rest her soul,

38:45.907 --> 38:47.737
and I could never leave her.

38:47.826 --> 38:49.036
♪

38:49.160 --> 38:50.830
I will do my best.

38:50.912 --> 38:52.292
♪

38:52.372 --> 38:53.962
I’ll get you started
on a course of penicillin

38:54.040 --> 38:55.420
for the cholangitis.

38:55.500 --> 38:57.790
You’ll be ready
for surgery tomorrow.

38:57.877 --> 38:59.377
It’s a date.

38:59.504 --> 39:00.344
[ chuckles ]

39:00.880 --> 39:02.090
[ chuckles ]

39:02.173 --> 39:04.263
[ knock at door ]

39:04.342 --> 39:05.682
♪

39:07.762 --> 39:09.062
Ah, Colonel.

39:09.180 --> 39:11.680
Please, come in.

39:11.808 --> 39:14.228
The, uh, muster roll,

39:14.352 --> 39:16.312
as requested by the governor.

39:17.647 --> 39:19.187
Splendid.

39:19.274 --> 39:22.154
You’ll find every man
who pledged his oath
to the militia.

39:24.279 --> 39:25.399
Since we’re parting ways
in the morning,

39:25.530 --> 39:27.570
would you consider
a game of chess?

39:27.699 --> 39:29.159
You bested me last time.

39:29.242 --> 39:31.242
Please give me the opportunity
to even the score.

39:34.038 --> 39:35.038
One game.

39:35.164 --> 39:37.424
That’s the spirit.

39:37.542 --> 39:39.002
Sit, please.

39:44.257 --> 39:46.717
Part of me envies you,

39:46.843 --> 39:49.723
that you’ll soon be home...

39:49.846 --> 39:51.676
resuming a citizen’s life.

39:51.764 --> 39:53.684
Hmm.

39:53.766 --> 39:55.766
Aye.

39:55.894 --> 39:57.944
It’s a relief

39:58.062 --> 40:00.902
to finally put down
the sword and pistol

40:00.982 --> 40:02.782
and pick up
the axe and shovel.

40:02.901 --> 40:05.441
Hmm.
Mm.

40:05.570 --> 40:07.410
One more soldier
lost to the land.

40:10.909 --> 40:12.409
[ melancholy music ]

40:12.535 --> 40:13.575
He died?

40:13.661 --> 40:16.621
♪

40:16.748 --> 40:18.248
Well, what happened?

40:18.333 --> 40:21.003
♪

40:21.085 --> 40:22.875
Anaphylaxis.

40:22.962 --> 40:25.262
Apparently,
a penicillin reaction.

40:25.340 --> 40:27.930
I’m sorry, Dr. Randall.

40:28.009 --> 40:29.889
Why wasn’t I notified?

40:29.969 --> 40:33.429
I‐I‐I don’t know.
I’m new here.

40:33.514 --> 40:35.564
[ sharply ]
Well, that’s no excuse.
I should’ve been called.

40:35.642 --> 40:36.772
I‐I’m so sorry.

40:36.893 --> 40:39.693
♪

40:39.771 --> 40:41.611
Thought I might
find you here.

40:41.731 --> 40:43.611
[ sighs ]

40:43.733 --> 40:45.783
Joe Abernathy.

40:45.902 --> 40:48.072
Doctor and a detective.

40:48.154 --> 40:51.324
Ah, The Impetuous Pirate.

40:51.449 --> 40:55.039
Just something I picked up
at the surgeon’s lounge.

40:55.119 --> 40:57.039
Who do you think put it there?

40:57.705 --> 41:00.325
I never took you
for a romance novel
kind of guy.

41:00.458 --> 41:02.588
Takes my mind off things.

41:02.669 --> 41:03.709
Yours too, I’m guessing.

41:05.630 --> 41:07.800
I must be the talk
of the third floor.

41:09.133 --> 41:11.223
The fourth floor by now.

41:16.474 --> 41:20.194
Something about
Graham Menzies...

41:23.648 --> 41:25.978
I let myself get attached
to the patient.

41:26.067 --> 41:28.357
It happens sometimes.

41:28.486 --> 41:31.236
Jesus, Claire,
we’re doctors, not robots.

41:31.322 --> 41:33.242
It’s not just that.

41:36.077 --> 41:39.577
Do you ever feel as if...

41:39.664 --> 41:42.334
as if everything is

41:42.417 --> 41:45.207
pointing you
towards something

41:45.336 --> 41:48.546
but you can’t quite put
your finger on what it is?

41:48.673 --> 41:53.183
I mean, you can feel it,
or you can sense it somehow.

41:53.261 --> 41:55.511
Ah, you’re going to think
I’ve come unhinged.

41:55.638 --> 41:57.598
[ laughs ]
Look,

41:57.682 --> 42:00.232
there’s clearly something
on your mind,

42:00.351 --> 42:01.851
but in my opinion,

42:01.936 --> 42:04.266
the problem
isn’t in the brain.

42:04.355 --> 42:07.435
The problem
is in the heart.

42:08.651 --> 42:11.491
[ warm music ]

42:11.571 --> 42:12.911
♪

42:13.031 --> 42:17.871
At the risk of sounding...
sentimental,

42:17.994 --> 42:20.124
had we gone to battle,

42:20.204 --> 42:22.414
there’s no man
I’d have rather had
by my side.

42:25.251 --> 42:27.091
That’s kind of you.

42:27.211 --> 42:28.551
[ chess piece clatters ]

42:28.629 --> 42:31.049
’Tis a rare thing
in this world to...

42:31.132 --> 42:33.382
meet people of a like mind.

42:34.385 --> 42:36.465
‐ Indeed.
‐ Hmm.

42:41.350 --> 42:44.690
And I know you share
many of my concerns:

42:44.771 --> 42:48.401
principally, that men
like Fitzgibbons never change.

42:50.443 --> 42:53.903
[ sighs ]
Our duty is to the law.

42:55.281 --> 42:57.241
We will see justice done.

42:58.326 --> 42:59.406
[ exhales sharply ]

43:03.414 --> 43:04.584
[ knock at door ]

43:04.665 --> 43:06.415
Hmm.
Excuse me.

43:11.923 --> 43:14.343
Ah, mm‐hmm.
Thank you.

43:14.425 --> 43:16.215
[ tense music ]

43:16.302 --> 43:18.602
‐ For your trouble.
‐ [ coins jingle ]

43:18.721 --> 43:21.771
♪

43:22.183 --> 43:24.773
Is that the document
you were expecting
from Scotland?

43:24.852 --> 43:28.772
Mm, a transcript
of the Ardsmuir prison roll
after Culloden.

43:28.856 --> 43:30.976
♪

43:31.109 --> 43:33.279
If I present this
to the governor

43:33.361 --> 43:35.281
and news of it
is circulated, then‐‐

43:35.404 --> 43:37.114
You’ll find my name
on that prison roll.

43:37.198 --> 43:39.278
♪

43:39.408 --> 43:40.778
Oh, I’m certain I will.

43:40.868 --> 43:43.408
♪

43:43.496 --> 43:47.706
I’m certain there is more
than one James Fraser
in Scotland.

43:47.792 --> 43:49.042
[ chuckles ]

43:49.127 --> 43:50.787
♪

43:50.878 --> 43:52.708
Aye...

43:52.797 --> 43:55.007
♪

43:55.133 --> 43:57.053
But only one
from Broch Tuarach.

43:57.135 --> 44:00.305
♪

44:25.788 --> 44:28.958
It is written here
that Fitzgibbons
has the surname Fraser.

44:29.041 --> 44:31.041
[ exhales sharply ]

44:31.169 --> 44:32.709
My godfather.

44:34.463 --> 44:37.343
Fitzgibbons
is his middle name.

44:37.425 --> 44:40.225
[ dramatic music ]

44:40.344 --> 44:41.934
♪

44:42.013 --> 44:44.723
What kind of deceitful devil
wears the guise of honor

44:44.849 --> 44:48.019
and talks of justice
and mercy?

44:48.144 --> 44:49.774
♪

44:49.854 --> 44:52.944
You released those men
in Hillsborough.

44:53.024 --> 44:54.574
[ scoffs ]

44:54.692 --> 44:58.202
Everything you did,
it was all for his sake.

44:58.279 --> 45:01.199
♪

45:01.282 --> 45:04.492
Believe of me what you will,

45:04.577 --> 45:07.537
but Murtagh Fitzgibbons Fraser
is a good man.

45:07.622 --> 45:10.542
♪

45:13.711 --> 45:16.921
As God is my witness,
I will do what must be done.

45:18.883 --> 45:20.723
Damned if I’ll be in league
with a traitor.

45:20.843 --> 45:22.143
I’m no traitor.

45:22.220 --> 45:23.550
I’ve cheated death

45:23.679 --> 45:26.389
in the duty
of other men’s ambitions.

45:26.474 --> 45:28.684
I’ve got the scars
to prove it.

45:28.768 --> 45:30.728
And I’ve done so
without complaint.

45:30.853 --> 45:34.773
But I will not stand by
and watch my kin
hunted like a dog

45:34.899 --> 45:37.569
for protecting those
that can’t protect themselves.

45:37.652 --> 45:39.652
Tryon will put a rope
around your neck.

45:39.737 --> 45:42.107
And tell me,

45:42.240 --> 45:44.580
what would you have done
in my place?

45:44.659 --> 45:47.579
♪

45:50.206 --> 45:52.786
I would never break my word,

45:52.917 --> 45:55.247
betray my oath
to king and country.

45:55.336 --> 45:58.506
♪

45:59.006 --> 46:01.336
You will do me the service
of standing down

46:01.425 --> 46:03.635
while I call for your arrest.

46:03.761 --> 46:06.601
[ disquieting music ]

46:06.681 --> 46:10.431
First and foremost,

46:10.518 --> 46:13.978
I swore an oath to my family.

46:14.105 --> 46:16.365
Surely you must understand.

46:16.440 --> 46:18.070
You’re a good man.

46:18.150 --> 46:20.360
♪

46:20.444 --> 46:23.454
I took a life in that jail,

46:23.572 --> 46:26.782
and you stood by
and pleaded for mercy
on their behalf.

46:26.867 --> 46:30.117
I believed you
were a good man.

46:30.246 --> 46:31.326
♪

46:31.455 --> 46:33.615
Which of us is it, then?

46:33.708 --> 46:35.538
Hmm?

46:35.626 --> 46:37.126
Which of us is righteous?

46:37.253 --> 46:39.803
♪

46:39.880 --> 46:41.130
Knox...

46:41.215 --> 46:43.375
It cannot be both.

46:43.467 --> 46:45.087
Knox!

46:45.177 --> 46:46.967
[ head thunks ]

46:47.054 --> 46:49.814
[ both grunting ]

46:49.932 --> 46:52.812
♪

47:09.493 --> 47:11.333
[ panting ]

47:11.454 --> 47:13.664
Forgive me...

47:13.748 --> 47:16.878
for not affording you
a soldier’s death.

47:17.001 --> 47:19.841
[ uneasy music ]

47:19.962 --> 47:22.842
♪

48:47.466 --> 48:49.756
[ coughing ]

48:49.844 --> 48:52.804
♪

49:01.105 --> 49:02.115
[ coughs ]

49:02.189 --> 49:05.069
♪

49:36.265 --> 49:37.895
[ cat meows ]

49:40.019 --> 49:42.099
Not a word,
or I’ll throttle ye.

49:42.188 --> 49:44.058
‐ MAN: Fire! Fire!
‐ [ bell ringing ]

49:44.148 --> 49:46.978
[ people clamoring ]

49:48.819 --> 49:50.899
Fetch a physician!

49:52.656 --> 49:54.526
[ coughing ]

49:54.658 --> 49:57.448
[ mournful music ]

49:57.536 --> 50:00.656
♪

50:08.547 --> 50:09.967
JAMIE:
Let’s go.

50:10.049 --> 50:11.929
Milord, it’s‐it’s
Lieutenant Knox.

50:12.009 --> 50:14.009
Yes. Nothing more
we can do for him.

50:14.136 --> 50:17.006
♪

50:24.813 --> 50:27.823
[ tranquil music ]

50:27.900 --> 50:30.860
♪

50:36.450 --> 50:38.370
[ horse whinnies ]

50:38.494 --> 50:41.374
♪

50:51.340 --> 50:54.050
[ both laughing ]

50:54.176 --> 50:57.096
♪

50:57.221 --> 50:58.101
Careful, Sassenach.

50:58.222 --> 50:59.062
What’s wrong?

50:59.181 --> 51:00.641
Eh.

51:00.724 --> 51:04.524
‐ [ cat meowing ]
‐ Found him in an alley,

51:04.603 --> 51:06.813
wanting for his mother’s milk.

51:06.897 --> 51:09.607
Mm, couldna leave him behind.

51:09.733 --> 51:11.533
He’s been surviving
on insects and earthworms.

51:11.610 --> 51:12.740
[ laughs ]

51:12.820 --> 51:14.700
Took an instant liking
to each other,

51:14.780 --> 51:16.410
did we no’, Adso?

51:16.490 --> 51:18.240
Adso?

51:18.325 --> 51:19.075
Is that a name?

51:19.201 --> 51:20.451
It is.

51:20.578 --> 51:21.578
Was the name
of my mother’s cat

51:21.662 --> 51:23.662
when I was a wee lad.

51:23.747 --> 51:25.537
This one here
is identical.

51:25.624 --> 51:27.334
[ chuckles ]

51:27.418 --> 51:29.128
Insects and earthworms.

51:29.253 --> 51:30.503
Aye.

51:30.588 --> 51:33.168
I bet you’d kill
for a saucer of milk.

51:33.257 --> 51:34.757
That was my intention.

51:34.883 --> 51:36.473
He can keep the vermin
from your surgery.

51:36.594 --> 51:39.394
[ laughs ]
They’d have to be
very small vermin.

51:39.471 --> 51:41.601
Ah, he’ll grow.

51:41.682 --> 51:44.432
♪

51:44.560 --> 51:46.440
Man.

51:46.520 --> 51:48.400
I guess you never really know
what’s coming, do you?

51:48.480 --> 51:50.110
♪

51:50.190 --> 51:51.440
No, you don’t.

51:51.567 --> 51:54.357
♪

51:54.445 --> 51:57.075
Actually, I’ve been thinking
about that a lot lately.

51:57.156 --> 51:59.526
♪

51:59.617 --> 52:03.747
How would you feel
about taking a trip
to London with me?

52:05.914 --> 52:07.584
I have finals, and‐‐

52:07.666 --> 52:09.836
After your exams.

52:12.296 --> 52:13.756
What about the hospital?

52:15.966 --> 52:20.256
Well, I’ve already requested
a leave of absence.

52:20.346 --> 52:22.306
You’re taking time off?

52:26.268 --> 52:27.978
Can’t believe it.

52:31.565 --> 52:34.145
Why London?

52:34.234 --> 52:37.364
Your father wanted to bring you
there before he died.

52:39.531 --> 52:40.821
Let me?

52:44.036 --> 52:46.076
I’d have to cancel
my summer classes.

52:46.163 --> 52:48.083
‐ Uh‐‐
‐ Please, Bree.

52:49.124 --> 52:52.344
It’s important to me
that we spend
this time together.

52:53.295 --> 52:56.165
[ somber music ]

52:56.298 --> 52:57.878
♪

52:58.008 --> 53:00.678
‐ [ cat meows ]
‐ Shh.

53:00.761 --> 53:03.351
♪

53:03.430 --> 53:05.350
Oh.

53:05.474 --> 53:07.354
[ laughs ]

53:07.476 --> 53:10.516
♪

53:10.938 --> 53:13.358
Thank you for my gift.

53:13.482 --> 53:16.192
♪

53:20.781 --> 53:23.491
I have much to tell you
about Hillsborough.

53:23.575 --> 53:26.195
♪

53:26.328 --> 53:27.868
But first,

53:27.996 --> 53:29.536
I can see you have something
on your mind.

53:29.665 --> 53:31.715
♪

53:31.792 --> 53:34.542
Do you remember me
telling you about a...

53:34.670 --> 53:36.710
a former patient of mine,

53:36.797 --> 53:39.797
Graham Menzies?

53:39.883 --> 53:41.643
Menzies.

53:41.719 --> 53:43.469
Aye.

53:43.554 --> 53:45.974
Aye, you told me his death
was but a rare occurrence.

53:46.056 --> 53:48.846
[ laughs softly ]
It was.

53:51.228 --> 53:54.308
Do you know
what I finally realized

53:54.398 --> 53:55.978
after all these years?

53:58.902 --> 54:00.572
Just how much I owe him.

54:02.906 --> 54:07.406
His death had
a profound effect on me,

54:07.536 --> 54:10.076
so much so that I took
a leave of absence from work

54:10.164 --> 54:13.214
and went to London
with Brianna,

54:13.292 --> 54:17.252
and that was where I learned
of Reverend Wakefield’s
passing.

54:20.257 --> 54:24.797
Had we not attended
that funeral,

54:24.928 --> 54:28.768
we would never
have crossed paths with Roger

54:28.849 --> 54:31.639
or...

54:31.769 --> 54:33.689
or found you.

54:33.771 --> 54:36.611
[ tender music ]

54:36.732 --> 54:39.532
♪

54:47.618 --> 54:49.448
Welcome home, Soldier.

54:49.536 --> 54:52.456
♪

54:58.879 --> 55:01.419
God the infinite,

55:01.507 --> 55:03.717
God the merciful,

55:03.801 --> 55:06.141
God the eternal.

55:06.220 --> 55:09.100
Someday, I will stand
before God,

55:09.181 --> 55:12.061
and I will receive answers
to all my questions

55:12.142 --> 55:14.892
about everything
in his universe,

55:14.978 --> 55:18.188
and I do have
many questions.

55:18.315 --> 55:21.735
But I won’t ask
about the nature of time.

55:21.819 --> 55:23.399
I’ve lived it.

55:23.487 --> 55:25.407
♪
